<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName genus="Rhoennanthus" lsidName="Rhoennanthus distafurcus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="distafurcus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Rhoennanthus distafurcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of other 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rhoenanthus)" class="Insecta" family="Potamanthidae" genus="Rhoenanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoenanthus (Rhoenanthus)" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Rhoenanthus">Rhoenanthus (Rhoenanthus)</taxonomicName>
species based on the following characteristics: i) subapical spine of the mandibular tusk well developed laterally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Larval morphology (head and mandibular tusk) A Potamanthus formosus Eaton, 1892 B Rhoenanthus magnificus Ulmer, 1920 C R. obscurus Navas, 1922 D angle measurement of mandibular tusk E R. distafurcus Bae &amp; McCafferty, 1991 F R. speciosus Eaton, 1881." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604591" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">10E</figureCitation>
), with a simple, short spine, ii) 16-20 medial rounded setae on mandibular tusk (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Larval morphology (head and mandibular tusk) A Potamanthus formosus Eaton, 1892 B Rhoenanthus magnificus Ulmer, 1920 C R. obscurus Navas, 1922 D angle measurement of mandibular tusk E R. distafurcus Bae &amp; McCafferty, 1991 F R. speciosus Eaton, 1881." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604591" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">10E</figureCitation>
) iii) length of the mandibular tusks ca 1.7-1.9
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of head, iv) length of foretibiae ca 1.19-1.25
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of the forefemora and about 2.5-2.8
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of the foretarsi, (v) leg with colour marking as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Larval morphology (foreleg) A Potamanthus formosus Eaton, 1892 B Rhoenanthus magnificus Ulmer, 1920 C R. obscurus Navas, 1922 D R. distafurcus Bae &amp; McCafferty, 1991 E R. speciosus Eaton, 1881. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604592" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">11D, and vi</figureCitation>
) lack of bipectinated setae on the mandible (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1076/0165-0424(200001)22:1;1-Z;FT009" author="Soldan, T" journalOrPublisher="Aquatic Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="9 - 17" refId="B20" refString="Soldan, T, Putz, M, 2000. The larva of Rhoenanthus distafurcus Bae et McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Potamanthidae) with notes on distribution and biology. Aquatic Insects 22 (1): 9 - 17, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1076/0165-0424(200001)22:1;1-Z;FT009" title="The larva of Rhoenanthus distafurcus Bae et McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Potamanthidae) with notes on distribution and biology." url="https://doi.org/10.1076/0165-0424(200001)22:1;1-Z;FT009" volume="22" year="2000">Soldan T and Putz M 2000)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
